"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972461","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-10-09","<p>DWP published an Equality Impact Assessment for Universal Credit in 2011, which stands overall, although in line with Ministers’ legal duties equality impacts have been considered on all major changes to Universal Credit.</p><p> </p><p>The Equality Impact Assessment can be accessed at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/universal-credit-equality-impact-assessment" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/universal-credit-equality-impact-assessment</a></p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-10-09T16:16:12.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972461/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972461/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972461/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-09-12","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when her Department undertook the most recent equality impact assessment of universal credit.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","174090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972462","Home Office","false","2018-10-09","<p>I can confirm that a substantive response will be sent within the week.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-10-09T16:01:19.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972462/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972462/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972462/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-09-12","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she plans to respond to the letter of 23 June 2018 from the hon. Member for Glasgow Central on the matter of a constituent, Habib Riaz.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","174069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972463","Home Office","false","2018-10-09","<p>The Government has welcomed the Interim Report of the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse and is carefully considering the recommendations directed at Government. We will respond fully in due course.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins","174045","2018-10-09T15:50:04.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972463/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972463/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972463/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-09-12","Child Sexual Abuse Independent Panel Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when he plans to publish the Government's response to the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse's Interim Report, published on 25 April 2018.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","174043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972464","Department for Education","false","2018-10-11","<p>The Department collects information from each local authority on the number of school places through the annual school capacity survey. The Department does not collect school capacity information at parliamentary constituency level. Data relating to the position in the 2017/18 academic year is currently being collected and quality assured. The latest published data held relates to the position in the 2016/17 academic year and can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/school-capacity-academic-year-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/school-capacity-academic-year-2016-to-2017</a>.</p><p>As of 1 May 2017 (2016/17 academic year), Wirral Local Authority had 27 primary schools that were full or had one or more pupils in excess of capacity, out of a total of 90 primary schools. Additional figures for the 2015/16 and 2014/15 academic years can be found in the table below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Primary schools in Wirral </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Academic Year</p></td><td><p>Number of primary <br>schools</p></td><td><p>Number of primary schools <br>that are full or have one or <br>more pupils in excess of <br>school capacity</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>90</p></td><td><p>27</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>90</p></td><td><p>25</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>90</p></td><td><p>24</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><br> Source: School Capacity survey</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-10-11T09:10:27.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972464/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972464/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972464/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-09-12","Primary Education: Wallasey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many primary schools in Wallasey constituency were full or oversubscribed in the school years commencing in (a) 2016, (b) 2017 and (c) 2018.","false","Biography information for Ms Angela Eagle","Wallasey","Ms Angela Eagle","173993"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972465","Department for Education","false","2018-10-11","<p>The Department collects information from each local authority on the number of school places through the annual school capacity survey (SCAP). The Department does not collect school capacity information at parliamentary constituency level. Data relating to the position in the 2017/2018 academic year is currently being collected and quality assured. The latest published data held relates to the position in the 2016/17 academic year and can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/school-capacity-academic-year-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/school-capacity-academic-year-2016-to-2017</a>.</p><p>As of 1 May 2017 (2016/17 academic year), Wirral Local Authority had two secondary schools that were full or had one or more pupils in excess of capacity, out of a total of 21 secondary schools. Additional figures for the 2015/16 and 2014/15 academic years can be found in the table below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Secondary schools in Wirral </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Academic Year</p></td><td><p>Number of <br>secondary schools</p></td><td><p>Number of secondary schools <br>that are full or have one or <br>more pupils in excess of school capacity</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>21</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>21</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>22</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: School Capacity survey</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-10-11T09:04:33.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972465/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972465/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972465/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-09-12","Secondary Education: Wallasey","1","House of Commons","T