"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972495","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-10-09","<p>The Government does not hold the requested information on convictions as this is a matter for the independent prosecuting authorities and the courts.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2018-10-09T09:37:24.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972495/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972495/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972495/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-09-12","Terrorism: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many convicted Republican terrorists, who were subsequently provided with letters of comfort by the Government have been re-convicted of a terrorism-related offence.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","174005"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972496","Home Office","false","2018-10-09","<p>The Government has welcomed the Interim Report of the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse and is carefully considering the recommendations directed at Government. We will respond fully in due course.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins","174043","2018-10-09T15:50:04.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972496/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972496/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972496/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-09-12","Child Sexual Abuse Independent Panel Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Mental Health and Inequalities of 19 June 2018, Official Report, Column 181, when he plans to respond to the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse's Interim Report, published on 25 April 2018.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","174045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972497","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-10-09","<p>Any terminal of MODNet, the Defence IT system, can be configured for use with the Defence Medical Services IT system (Defence Medical Information Capability Programme - DMICP). In addition, 214 DMICP laptops are available for deployed operations and exercises. As an illustrative snapshot, in August 2018 there were 5,746 unique users (fixed and deployed) registered on the system.</p><p> </p><p>DMICP went live at the first medical facility, at Chicksands, on 16 February 2007 and was then rolled out site by site. Since DMICP was introduced, it has been subject to a number of changes and improvements. Defence is in the process of replacing DMICP to better support the delivery of healthcare. In the meantime, updates continue to be made to improve performance.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","174007","2018-10-09T15:06:40.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972497/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972497/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972497/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-09-12","Defence Medical Services: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many user terminals there are in the Defence Medical Services IT system.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","174006"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972498","Department for Education","false","2018-10-09","<p>Work on supporting students in making the transition into university and on exploring disclosure agreements has continued to progress in the period since formal announcement of these policy areas was made in June.</p><p>Stakeholders from across the sector have been involved in this work and will continue to be called on to contribute in the specific areas where their expertise can add most value.</p><p>We shall also be working with parents and carers, and legal and health experts as well as sector partners in the specific area of developing advice on disclosure and consent, as highlighted in the suicide prevention guidance published on 5 September by Universities UK.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","174037","2018-10-09T16:43:44.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972498/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972498/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972498/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-09-12","Students: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what progress his Department has made on setting up a working group on the transition students face when going to university as part of his measures to support student mental health.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","174036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972499","Department for Education","false","2018-10-09","<p>Work on supporting students in making the transition into university and on exploring disclosure agreements has continued to progress in the period since formal announcement of these policy areas was made in June.</p><p>Stakeholders from across the sector have been involved in this work and will continue to be called on to contribute in the specific areas where their expertise can add most value.</p><p>We shall also be working with parents and carers, and legal and health experts as well as sector partners in the specific area of developing advice on disclosure and consent, as highlighted in the suicide prevention guidance published on 5 September by Universities UK.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","174036","2018-10-09T16:43:44.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972499/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972499/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972499/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-09-12","Students: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many meetings his Department held with stakeholders to explore the opt-in requirement for universities to have permission to share information on student mental health with parents or a trusted person since June 2018.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","174037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972500","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-09","<p>As at the end of August, the Department had:</p><p>- 1,522 staff employed directly;</p><p>- 76 people seconded in; and</p><p>- 214 staff working under contract.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-10-09T12:38:46.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972500/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972500/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972500/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-09-12","Department of Health and Social Care: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many staff (a) are employed directly by (b) are seconded to and (c) work under contract to his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","174092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972501","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-10-09","<p>As of 31 August 2018, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office has:</p><p>a) 4,544 UK-based staff employed directly (of which 583 are on inward interchange loan from other government departments);<br>b) five staff on secondment;<br>c) 95 staff on contract to the FCO.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-10-09T12:28:37.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972501/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972501/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972501/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-09-12","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many staff (a) are employed directly by (b) are seconded to and (c) work under contract to his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","174093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972502","Treasury","false","2018-10-15","As at 31<sup>st</sup> July 2018 the headcounts were as follows: a) 1326 staff employed directly by the department b) 74 staff seconded to the department c) 14 staff working under contract","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2018-10-15T15:02:22.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972502/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972502/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972502/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-12","Treasury: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many staff (a) are employed directly by (b) are seconded to and (c) work under contract to his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","174094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972503","Home Office","false","2018-10-10","<p>Home Office publish monthly workforce management information on gov.uk - links provided below. This information has been summarised in the table 1 provided.</p><p>2010 to 2017: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/structure-and-salaries-series" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/structure-and-salaries-series</a></p><p>2018: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/workforce-management-information-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/workforce-management-information-2018</a></p><p> </p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-10-10T16:28:33.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972503/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972503/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972503/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-09-12","Home Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many staff (a) are employed directly by (b) are seconded to and (c) work under contract to his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","174095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972504","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-10-25","<p>The number of staff employed directly by the Department as at 1 April 2018 is 56,870. This is published in the Biannual Civilian Report, the April 2018 version of which can be found at:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/mod-biannual-civilian-personnel-report-2018</p><p>There are currently 112 individuals in the Department who are seconded from other organisations.</p><p>The number of people who work under contract in the Department is not held in the format requested.</p>","Pudsey","Stuart Andrew",,"2018-10-25T14:03:14.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972504/answer","Biography information for Stuart Andrew","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972504/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972504/answer","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972504/answer/previousversion/78302","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","11","Defence","Defence","2018-09-12","Ministry of Defence: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many staff (a) are employed directly by (b) are seconded to and (c) work under contract to his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","174096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972505","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-10-09","<p>As of 31 August 2018, the Department employed 2115 or 2063.6 full-time equivalent staff (fte) in either a directly employed, inward interchange, or contingent labour basis, broken down as follows:</p><ol><li><p>Directly employed – 1960 staff / 1911.5 fte, of which;</p><ol><li><p>1862 / 1815.8 fte are currently on payroll</p></li><li><p>98 / 95.7 fte are on unpaid leave of absence</p></li></ol></li><li><p>Inward interchange – 112 staff / 109.1 fte, of which;</p><ol><li><p>75 / 73.3 fte are employed on inward loans</p></li><li><p>37 / 35.8 are employed on inward secondments</p></li></ol></li><li><p>Contingent labour – 43 staff / 43 fte</p></li></ol>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2018-10-09T14:51:12.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972505/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972505/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972505/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-09-12","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many staff (a) are employed directly by (b) are seconded to and (c) work under contract to his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","174097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972506","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-10-15","<p>The EU Copyright Directive, which the Government supports, is currently in trilogue. The European Commission produced an initial impact assessment which looked across all affected sectors, including the creative industries. Additionally, the Intellectual Property Office has met extensively with stakeholders from the affected sectors, including the creative industries, to understand the potential impact of any changes.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-10-15T12:47:48.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972506/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972506/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972506/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-09-12","Arts: Copyright","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the EU Copyright Directive on the creative industries.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","174035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972507","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-10-09","<p>As at June 2018, there were 68,202 FTE staff employed directly by the Ministry of Justice (including all its Agencies) and 4,599 FTE staff under contract to the department. Data are not held centrally on the number of secondments.</p><p> </p><p>These data are available at:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/workforce-management-information-moj.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2018-10-09T17:08:44.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972507/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972507/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972507/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-09-12","Ministry of Justice: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many staff (a) are employed directly by (b) are seconded to and (c) work under contract to his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","174098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972508","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-10-09","<p>The Northern Ireland Office employs 119 staff directly, 34 staff on secondment and fewer than 5 staff are working under contract.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2018-10-09T09:58:05.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972508/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972508/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972508/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-09-12","Northern Ireland Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many staff (a) are employed directly by (b) are seconded to and (c) work under contract to his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","174099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972509","Scotland Office","false","2018-10-10","<p>The Office of the Secretary of State for Scotland does not employ staff directly. All staff that join do so on assignment, loan or secondment from other government bodies, principally the Ministry of Justice and the Scottish Government. No staff are on contracts directly with the Office of the Secretary of State for Scotland.</p><p>Specific details can be found in the staffing section of the Scotland Office Annual report 2017/18:</p><p><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/728570/Scottish_Office_Annual_Report_2017-18.pdf" target="_blank">Scotland Office Annual Report 2017/18</a></p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2018-10-10T14:27:53.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972509/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972509/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972509/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2018-09-12","Scotland Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many staff (a) are employed directly by (b) are seconded to and (c) work under contract to his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","174100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972510","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-10-09","<p>Any terminal of MODNet, the Defence IT system, can be configured for use with the Defence Medical Services IT system (Defence Medical Information Capability Programme - DMICP). In addition, 214 DMICP laptops are available for deployed operations and exercises. As an illustrative snapshot, in August 2018 there were 5,746 unique users (fixed and deployed) registered on the system.</p><p> </p><p>DMICP went live at the first medical facility, at Chicksands, on 16 February 2007 and was then rolled out site by site. Since DMICP was introduced, it has been subject to a number of changes and improvements. Defence is in the process of replacing DMICP to better support the delivery of healthcare. In the meantime, updates continue to be made to improve performance.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","174006","2018-10-09T15:06:40.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972510/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972510/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972510/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-09-12","Defence Medical Services: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when the IT system used by Defence Medical Services was introduced; and whether that system has been upgraded.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","174007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972511","Wales Office","false","2018-10-09","<p>The Office of the Secretary of State for Wales does not employ staff directly. All staff working at the Office are employed by the Ministry of Justice (MOJ).</p><p>2.3 (FTE) staff are seconded to the Office from the Government Legal Department.</p><p>There are no staff working under contract to the Department. Contractors delivering services to the Office do so under other government departments’ contracts.</p>","Eastleigh","Mims Davies",,"2018-10-09T10:06:27.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972511/answer","Biography information for Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972511/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972511/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2018-09-12","Wales Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many staff (a) are employed directly by (b) are seconded to and (c) work under contract to his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","174101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972512","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-09","<p>On 31 March 2018, at the Department no individuals working in the inner or outer London pay regions were paid less than the London Living Wage of £10.20. Similarly, no individuals in the national pay region were paid less than the United Kingdom Living Wage of £8.75.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-10-09T10:57:29.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972512/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972512/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972512/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-09-12","Department of Health and Social Care: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many staff in his Department that work (a) inside and (b) outside Greater London are paid at a rate below the Real Living Wage.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","174102"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972513","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-10-09","<p>No Foreign and Commonwealth Office UK-based staff are paid at a rate below the Real Living Wage either inside or outside Greater London.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-10-09T12:06:33.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972513/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972513/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972513/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-09-12","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many staff in his Department that work (a) inside and (b) outside Greater London are paid at a rate below the  Real Living Wage.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","174103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972514","Treasury","false","2018-10-09","<p>No staff directly employed by HM Treasury who work inside London are paid at a rate below the London Living Wage.</p><p> </p><p>No staff directly employed by HM Treasury who work outside Greater London are paid at a rate below the UK Living Wage (also known as the Real Living Wage).</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-10-09T15:40:15.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972514/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972514/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972514/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-12","Treasury: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many staff in his Department that work (a) inside and (b) outside Greater London are paid at a rate below the Real Living Wage.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","174104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972515","Home Office","false","2018-10-09","<p>In April 2016, the Government introduced a higher minimum wage rate, called the National Living Wage, which all employers in the UK are required to pay to those aged 25 and over.</p><p>The Home Office is compliant with April 2018 National Living Wage of £7.83 and pays this regardless of age. The Living Wage Foundation (LWF) is an initiative by Citizens UK which advocates employers paying an alternative hourly rate known as the Real Living Wage or London Real Living Wage. The current Real Living Wage is £8.75 and London Real Living Wage is £10.20. Currently there are 4 directly employed staff being paid marginally below the Real Living Wage Foundation rate</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins","174805","2018-10-09T15:55:32.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972515/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972515/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972515/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-09-12","Home Office: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many staff in his Department that work (a) inside and (b) outside Greater London are paid at a rate below the Real Living Wage.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","174105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972516","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-10-09","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) pays over and above the National Living Wage, which was increased to £7.83 per hour in April 2018. The MOD has not formally signed up to the Living Wage Rates, as defined by the Living Wage Foundation. In 2015 the then Secretary of State for Defence agreed that all London-based staff should be paid at least the equivalent of the Living Wage Foundation's London Living Wage rate. The MOD continues to pay above that rate.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","174806","2018-10-09T15:05:33.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972516/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972516/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972516/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-09-12","Ministry of Defence: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many staff in his Department that work (a) inside and (b) outside Greater London are paid at a rate below the Real Living Wage.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","174106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972517","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-10-15","<p>The UK Living Wage (sometimes referred to as the ‘Real Living Wage’) and the London Living Wage, are both voluntary rates set by the Living Wage Foundation.</p><p> </p><p>These are not statutory figures which relate to the government policy in this area, and so are not legally binding on employers. The statutory minimum rates are the National Living Wage and the National Minimum Wage.</p><p> </p><p>For comparison, the National Living Wage is currently £7.83 per hour, and increased by 4.4% in April 2018.</p><p> </p><p>The increases in the National Living Wage and the National Minimum Wage have produced increases for over 2 million workers this year, across the economy, and increased pay by £2,000 for those on the minimum rate, since these statutory arrangements were introduced.</p><p> </p><p>All MoJ employees are paid at least the National Minimum Wage and the National Living Wage.</p><p> </p><p>395 staff employed by the Ministry of Justice (MoJ HQ, HMCTS, LAA, OPD and CICA) and 24 by HMPPS work inside Greater London are paid at a rate below the London Real Living Wage £10.20 per hour.</p><p> </p><p>1479 staff employed by the Ministry of Justice (MoJ HQ, HMCTS, LAA, OPD and CICA) and 543 by HMPPS work outside Greater London are paid at a rate below the National Real Living Wage £8.75 per hour.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2018-10-15T14:56:31.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972517/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972517/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972517/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-09-12","Ministry of Justice: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many staff in his Department that work (a) inside and (b) outside Greater London are paid at a rate below the Real Living Wage.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","174107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972518","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-10-09","<p>Other than short-term interns, no directly employed staff are paid less than the hourly rate of pay determined by the Real Living Wage.</p><p>The Department follows the Government's best practice guidance relating to the minimum wage, work experience and internships and Living Wage accreditation does not require employers to pay the Living Wage to volunteers, apprentices or interns. At the end of August 2018 the Department employed 12 summer interns on contracts lasting no longer than 12 weeks. Interns employed on this basis, both inside and outside of Greater London, earned at least £9.36 per hour which is above the recommended national minimum wage of £7.38 per hour.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2018-10-09T15:16:32.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972518/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972518/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972518/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-09-12","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many staff in his Department that work (a) inside and (b) outside Greater London are paid at a rate below the Real Living Wage.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","174108"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972519","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-10-10","<p>No staff working for the Northern Ireland Office inside or outside Greater London is paid at a rate below the Real Living Wage as defined by the Living Wage Foundation.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2018-10-10T09:12:36.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972519/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972519/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972519/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-09-12","Northern Ireland Office: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many staff in her Department that work (a) inside and (b) outside Greater London are paid at a rate below the Real Living Wage.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","174109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972520","Scotland Office","false","2018-10-10","<p>No staff that work in the Office of the Secretary of State for Scotland, located inside and outside Greater London, are paid below the Real Living Wage. The Office of the Secretary of State for Scotland does not employ staff directly. All staff that join do so on assignment, loan or secondment from other government bodies, principally the Ministry of Justice and the Scottish Government.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2018-10-10T14:29:17.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972520/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972520/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972520/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2018-09-12","Scotland Office: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many staff in his Department that work (a) inside and (b) outside Greater London are paid at a rate below the Real Living Wage.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","174110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972521","Wales Office","false","2018-10-09","<p>Staff in the Office of the Secretary of State for Wales are based in either London or Cardiff.</p><p>All staff based in our London office are paid at a rate above the London Living Wage and all staff based in our Cardiff office are paid at a rate above the UK Living Wage (Real Living Wage).</p><p> </p>","Eastleigh","Mims Davies","174811","2018-10-09T10:08:52.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972521/answer","Biography information for Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972521/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972521/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2018-09-12","Wales Office: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many staff in his Department that work (a) inside and (b) outside Greater London are paid at a rate below the Real Living Wage.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","174111"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972522","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-10","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) is currently evaluating cerliponase alfa for use in the treatment of neuronal ceroid lipofuscinosis type 2, through its highly specialised technologies programme. NICE published draft guidance on cerliponase alfa in February 2018 that does not recommend use of the drug as there is considerable uncertainty about the long-term effects of the drug.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England is in discussions with Biomarin, the manufacturer of cerliponase alfa, to seek to agree a managed access agreement (MAA) that may address the uncertainty and enable NICE to recommend the drug as value for money. Cerliponase alfa is not therefore currently routinely funded on the National Health Service, but NHS England and the company are working jointly to agree a MAA.</p><p> </p><p>In the absence of final guidance from NICE, clinicians can apply to NHS England for funding in exceptional cases through the individual funding request process.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-10-10T12:41:01.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972522/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972522/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972522/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-09-12","Brineura","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to make cerliponase alfa available to eligible children in advance of an agreement being signed between NHS and the manufacturer of the drug.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","173983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972523","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-10","<p>The Department has no plans to review the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence’s (NICE) criteria for assessing medicines. NICE is an independent body and is responsible for the methods and processes it uses in the development of its guidance. NICE’s methods and processes for the assessment of drugs have been carefully developed over time through extensive engagement with stakeholders and are internationally respected. NICE continues to keep its procedures under periodic review to ensure that they remain fit for purpose.</p><p> </p><p>All topics, including drugs for rare diseases, are considered through a rigorous topic selection process before formal referral to NICE to ensure that NICE guidance is appropriate and will add value. NICE assesses most significant new drugs through its technology appraisal programme and has been able to recommend a number of drugs licenced for the treatment of rare diseases for routine use on the National Health Service.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-10-10T12:42:22.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972523/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972523/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972523/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-09-12","Rare Diseases: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether his Department has plans to review NICE’s criteria for reviewing new medicines so that it ensures appropriate access to treatments by people with rare diseases.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","173984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972524","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-15","<p>The NHS England service specifications for Metabolic disorders (children) and Metabolic disorders (adults) both include ceroid lipofuscinosis type 2 (CLN2). These can be found on the NHS England website at the following links:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/e06-metab-disorders-child.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/e06-metab-disorders-child.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/e06-metab-disorders-adult.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/e06-metab-disorders-adult.pdf</a></p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-10-15T14:54:04.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972524/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972524/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972524/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-09-12","Brineura","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, for what reason there is no national service specification for ceroid lipofuscinosis type 2 (CLN2).","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","173985"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972525","Treasury","false","2018-10-09","<p>The Statement of Funding Policy will be reviewed and updated as part of the next Spending Review. Since the 2015 edition, funding arrangements to reflect powers devolved through the Scotland Act 2016 and Wales Act 2017 have been separately updated in the Scottish and Welsh Governments’ respective Fiscal Frameworks.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-10-09T14:40:54.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972525/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972525/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972525/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-12","Devolution: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, when his Department plans to publish the next edition of the Statement of funding policy: funding the Scottish Parliament, National Assembly for Wales and Northern Ireland Assembly.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","174077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972526","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-10-09","<p>The Government has received 2,196 representations in response to the consultation <em>Powers for dealing with unauthorised development and encampments</em>.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-10-09T14:57:50.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972526/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972526/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972526/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-09-12","Travellers: Caravan Sites","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many responses were received to the consultation, Powers for dealing with unauthorised development and encampments, which closed on 15 June 2018.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","174008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972708","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-09-25","<p>The UK Government notes the recent announcement by the Sudanese National Congress Party (NCP) that it has selected President Bashir as its candidate for the 2020 Presidential election. Through bilateral engagement at Ministerial and official level, the UK continues to urge the Government of Sudan to implement swiftly the recommendations of the National Dialogue process and undertake political reforms that strengthen Sudan's democracy. This will ensure that the elections are free, fair, and inclusive. During a visit to Khartoum in August, the Minister for Africa urged the Government of Sudan to create a political environment that is conducive to freedom of expression and political affiliation. I also raised the importance of a stable and pluralistic political enviroment during my recent visit to Sudan in September.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-09-25T15:44:25.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972708/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972708/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972708/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-09-12","Sudan: Politics and Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the announcement by Field Marshal Bashir, President of Sudan, that he intends to seek changes to the constitution to enable him to remain in office.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL10294"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972709","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-09-25","<p>The biannual UK-Sudan Strategic Dialogue provides an important platform for the UK and Sudan to raise issues of concern and discuss areas where we can work together. The Dialogue provides a framework for us to deliver on bilateral priorities, including the peace process, human rights, development, migration, trade, and counter-terrorism. Reviewing progress on these issues will form a central part of the next round of the Strategic Dialogue, scheduled to take place in October<strong>.</strong></p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-09-25T15:44:48.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972709/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972709/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972709/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-09-12","Sudan: Foreign Relations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what benchmarks they have set for their forthcoming strategic dialogue with the Republic of Sudan.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL10295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972711","Department for International Development","false","2018-09-21","<p>The UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA) reports that 1.6 million Internally Displaced People are living in Darfur. Over 300,000 Sudanese refugees remain in Chad. The UN estimated in July that the number of people requiring urgent food assistance (in phases 3 and 4 of the Integrated Food Security Phase Classification system) is expected to rise to 6.2 million. The UK is continuing to monitor the situation closely.</p><p>A voluntary programme for the safe and dignified repatriation of Darfuri refugees from Chad, administered by the office of the UN High Commissioner for Refugees and the Governments of Sudan and Chad, is ongoing. Since the programme began in April, around 350 refugees have returned to their places of residence in Darfur.</p><p>The security situation has evolved in much of Darfur, and therefore it makes sense that the UN-AU Mission in Darfur (UNAMID) should also change. The UN Security Council resolution adopted in July this year provides the Mission with a mandate that fits the evolving situation. Nevertheless, while there have been improvements, we recognise that the security situation remains fragile. We therefore continue to support a gradual, conditions-based withdrawal of UNAMID, contingent upon a fully benchmarked exit strategy, to ensure that improvements in the security situation are sustained.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2018-09-21T11:48:44.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972711/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972711/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972711/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-09-12","Darfur: Armed Conflict","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many internally displaced people they estimate to be living in Darfur; how many Darfuri refugees they estimate to be living in Chad; whether they consider it safe for displaced people and refugees to return to their homes; what are their estimates of food shortages and the potential for famine in the region; whether they consider it would be safe for the United Nations–African Union Mission in Darfur to withdraw their peacekeepers from Darfur by 2020; and if so, on what grounds they reached that conclusion.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL10296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972712","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-09-25","<p>Human rights remain a key priority for our engagement with the Government of Sudan, and we will continue to pursue our human rights objectives through the UK-Sudan Strategic Dialogue. During our recent visits to Sudan, the Minister for Africa, Harriett Baldwin MP, and I discussed the need for the Government of Sudan to make concerted efforts to improve the human rights situation.</p><p>We have received a number of reports of restrictions on freedom of expression and the media, including the detention of opposition figures, the arrest of journalists, and the suppression of publications. We regularly raise these at a senior level with the Government of Sudan. Freedom of expression is a basic human right and we continue to make clear to the Government of Sudan that the Sudanese people must be allowed to exercise their rights freely.</p><p>While there is generally freedom of worship in Sudan, our Embassy in Khartoum has had reports of a number of restrictions on freedom of religion or belief, including limitations to Christian school opening days, the demolition of churches, and the lashing of women. I held a roundtable with religious leaders during my recent visit, and raised these issues with the Government. The promotion of freedom of religion or belief as a means of enhancing tolerance and inclusion remains a key part of our engagement with Sudan.</p><p>The UK continues to make clear our strong opposition to the use of the death penalty, and of mutilation as a punishment, in all circumstances.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-09-25T15:40:30Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972712/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972712/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972712/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-09-12","Sudan: Human Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what reports from Sudan they have received over the past 12 months about (1) the arrest of opposition politicians, (2) violations of religious freedom, (3) the arrest of journalists and bloggers, (4) the suppression of publications, (5) the lashing of women for failing to wear acceptable clothing, and (6) statements by Field Marshal Bashir calling for the reintroduction of amputations and executions.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL10297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972713","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-09-25","<p>British Government officials avoid all non-essential contact with individuals indicted by the International Criminal Court (ICC). We continue to abide by EU guidance that &quot;essential contact&quot; includes engagement strictly required for carrying out core diplomatic or consular activities.</p><p>It is for private individuals to make their own decisions about whether to hold meetings with ICC indictees.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-09-25T15:45:11.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972713/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972713/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972713/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-09-12","Sudan: British Nationals Abroad","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their policy on civil servants, businessmen, or British visitors to Sudan meeting Field Marshal Bashir following his indictment by the International Criminal Court for genocide and crimes against humanity.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL10298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972714","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-09-25","<p>The UK remains concerned by the situation in Darfur and the Two Areas (South Kordofan and Blue Nile). We welcome the extension of the unilateral cessation of hostilities in Darfur by the Sudan Liberation Movement-Minni Minawi (SLM-MM), SLM-Transitional Council (SLM-TC) and the Justice and Equality Movement (JEM) until 6 November 2018 and by the Government of Sudan until 31 December 2018. We urge all parties to the conflict to abide by these cessations of hostilities and to resume urgently the negotiations on a permanent ceasefire. We have encouraged the new leadership of the SPLM-N in the Two Areas to engage with the mediators to help us understand their aspirations for the peace process.</p><p>The UK is disappointed not to have seen progress on the agreement of a permanent, country wide ceasefire and full humanitarian access to all conflict areas since the AUHIP Roadmap was signed in 2016. The peace process should not be held back by wider political disagreements. We therefore urge all sides to lose no further time in returning to the negotiating table.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-09-25T15:46:01.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972714/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972714/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972714/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-09-12","Sudan: Peace Negotiations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their latest assessment of progress in the peace process in (1) Darfur, and (2) Blue Nile and Kordofan.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL10299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972716","Department for Transport","false","2018-09-24","<p>The Department for Transport is currently working with Network Rail, Gatwick Airport Ltd and other stakeholders to develop proposals for enhancing Gatwick Airport rail station in order to relieve pedestrian congestion at the station. As part of this work the Department and Network Rail have had numerous and ongoing discussions with Govia Thameslink Railway, the parent company of Gatwick Express.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2018-09-24T11:37:52.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972716/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972716/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/972716/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-09-12","Gatwick Airport Station","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what discussions, if any, they have had with Gatwick Express about proposals to re-develop Gatwick Airport railway station to manage congestion.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradshaw",,"Lord Bradshaw","HL10300"
